The functional groups of CQDs were confirmed by FTIR, as shown in Fig. 2
                        . The CQDs obtained hydroxyl groups since the intense peaks at 3290, 1420, and 1010 cm−1 were assigned to O–H stretching, O–H bending, and C–O stretching, respectively [18]. The absorption bands at 2920 and 1580 cm−1 were assigned to C–H stretching and CC stretching of the carbon atoms with sp2/sp3 hybridization, respectively [18]. The chemical composition and surface properties of CQDs were further investigated by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) (Fig. 3
                        ). The survey spectrum of CQDs confirmed the presence of carbon (C1s, 36.62 %), oxygen (O1s, 59.46 %), and nitrogen (N1s, 2.00 %), with the peak at 285 eV, 532 eV, and 399 eV, respectively (Fig. 3a) [31]. In the high-resolution spectra, the peak of C1s spectra at 285.0 eV (23 %), 286.5 eV (57 %), 287.9 eV (17 %), and 289.1 eV (3 %) could be assigned to CC/C–C, C-O, CO, and COOH, respectively (Fig. 3b) [18]. The N1s spectra of CQDs show two peaks at 399.7 eV (C-N-C, 52 %) and 400.9 eV (N–H, 48 %) (Fig. 3c) [31]. The high-resolution O1s spectra reveal peaks at 531.5 eV (C-OH, 4 %), 533.0 eV (C-O-C, 64 %), 534.0 eV (CO, 27 %), and 535.1 eV (Na KLL, 5 %) (Fig. 3d) [18]. These results suggest that CQDs display hydroxyl, amine, and carboxyl groups conjugated to an sp2/sp3-hybridized carbon framework to increase solubility and stability [28].

The selectivity of CQDs-GSH toward diverse metal ions (2.0 mM), including As5+, As3+, Ce3+, Cd2+, Co2+, Ca2+, Mg2+, Ni2+, Cu2+, Pb2+, Zn2+, Hg2+, Fe2+, and Fe3+, was performed under fluorescence excitation at 300 nm (Fig. 5
                        ). The “turn on” fluorescence emission of CQDs-GSH was drastically quenched with Hg2+, Fe2+, and Fe3+, observed by no fluorescence emission under UV light (365 nm) (Fig. 5a). Other d-group metal ions, including As5+ and Cu2+, decreased the fluorescence intensity of CQDs-GSH by about 60 %. However, other divalent metal ions belonging to s-group metal ions, such as Ca2+ and Mg2+, can bind with CQDs-GSH, presenting a reduction in half of the fluorescence emission. In addition, other heavy metal ions such as Cd2+, Co2+, Pb2+, Zn2+, Ni2+, and Pb2+ slightly quenched the fluorescence emission of CQDs-GSH. From the selectivity test, CQDs-GSH was selective to As5+, Hg2+, Fe2+, and Fe3+ over other metal ions. Furthermore, the zeta potential values of CQDs-GSH (0.1 mg/mL) in the presence of these metal ions (0.2 mM) were investigated in deionized water by the DLS method (Table 1
                        ). The zeta potentials of CQDs-GSH in the presence of Hg2+, Fe2+, and Fe3+ ions positively increased compared to that of the CQDs-GSH, indicating that the glutathione on the surface of CQDs was capable of recognizing these ions due to the thiol group or carbonyl groups [35]. On the other hand, the zeta potential of CQDs-GSH in the presence of As5+ negatively decreases due to the overall negative charge of HAsO4
                        2− molecules. This behavior collectively represents that the interaction of glutathione consists of the thiol group or cysteine amino acid, which can detect arsenic ions [36]. Hg2
                        + has a high affinity for thiol groups (−SH) and C=O groups of CQDs-GSH, resulting in fluorescence quenching via electrostatic interaction and non-radiative electron transfer from the oxygen-containing groups of CQDs-GSH and Hg2+ ions [37]. The interaction between the hydroxyl groups on the surface of the CQDs-GSH and Fe species (Fe2+ and Fe3+) contributes to fluorescence quenching by involving charge transfer and controlled exciton recombination [29].
